==English==
===Noun===
'''truthiness'''

# truthiness refers to the quality by which someone purports to know something emotionally or instinctively, without regard to evidence or to what the person might conclude from intellectual examination.
# the [[quality]] by which one is [[convinced]] of a [[belief]], to the [[neglect]] of [[observable]] facts or of [[rational]] thought
# the quality of [[adhering]] to concepts one wishes or believes to be true, rather than the facts
# variation of ''truthfulness'', ''faithfulness'', derivational [[morpheme]] of "truthy"; archaic and rare or dialectal

===Origination===
 
: (1) The premiere episode of the popular television show, "The Colbert Report"
: (2) Unknown origin circa 1824; [[OED]] cites publication in 1854 [http://itre.cis.upenn.edu/~myl/languagelog/archives/002586.html]

===Quotations===
* '''[1844] 1854''', ''Memoirs of Joseph John Gurney,'' Joseph Bevan Braithwaite ed. [http://www.hti.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=moa;cc=moa;idno=AGV9015.0002.001;view=image;seq=00000449]
*: How delightful have the Scriptures been to me of late seasons! I have been struck with the '''''truthiness''''' which is so evident in their apparent contradictions. These are generally capable of being easily reconciled; but they do indeed mark the genuineness and authenticity of the whole.
* '''[1882] c. 1890''' ''Noctes Ambrosianae,'' cited in ''The Century Dictionary'' [http://www.leoyan.com/century-dictionary.com/cent2jpgframes.php?volno=08&page=6514]
*: '''''Truthiness''''' is a habit, like every other virtue.  There I hold by the Peripatetics. 
* '''2006''', Thomas Blood, “Truthiness, Justices, and the Americano Way” [http://spaces.msn.com/docblood/Blog/cns!1pOXlBXwKbnpU5SIJkWEgw2w!3836.entry]
*: I am not so naïve as to believe that anyone is in possession of the “absolute truth.”  Perhaps there is no such thing.  However, having some measure of how to evaluate truth from “'''truthiness'''” would be a wonderful thing to have.

